<header class="hero">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <div class="eyebrow">Explainer</div>
    <h1 style="font-size:42px">LIHTC is not an affordable housing program. It's a <span>tax shelter</span> we asked to become one.</h1>
    <p class="deck">
      And it can't. That's not a bug. It's a tax instrument working exactly as tax instruments
      work — which is why, thirty years in, people lose their homes.
    </p>
  </div>
</header>

<main class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <article class="prose">

      <h2 style="margin-top:0">The short version</h2>
      <p>The Low-Income Housing Tax Credit is the largest source of affordable housing finance in the United States. In most places it is effectively the <em>only</em> one. It has built millions of homes, and for thirty years it kept my rent at a level I could pay.</p>
      <p>It was also never designed to do this job. It was designed to move investment capital, and it produces housing the way a factory produces heat — as a byproduct of doing something else. Once you see that, everything that seems inexplicable about LIHTC stops being inexplicable.</p>
      <p>Including the part where it ends.</p>

      <h2>Where it came from</h2>
      <p>LIHTC was created in the <strong>Tax Reform Act of 1986</strong> — a law whose central purpose was to <em>eliminate</em> tax shelters in real estate. As Congress was closing the old preferences, it opened a new one, narrowly targeted at low-income rental housing. Nobody in 1986 expected it to become the country's housing policy. It became that by default, because over the following decades almost everything else was cut.</p>
      <p>Public housing construction ended. Federal new-construction subsidies dried up. What survived was the one program structured as a tax credit rather than an appropriation — which meant it never had to fight for its life in an annual budget the way a spending program does. Shelterforce calls it <strong>the only tool in the box</strong>, and that is not a metaphor.</p>

      <blockquote>LIHTC didn't win the argument about how to build affordable housing. It outlived everything that would have argued with it.</blockquote>

      <h2>How dominant is it, actually?</h2>
      <p>More than most people believe, and the exact figure is genuinely contested — so here is the honest range rather than the loudest number.</p>

      <table>
        <tr><th>Figure</th><th>What it measures</th></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>51%</strong></td><td>of existing federally subsidized homes received LIHTC — the solid number (NHPD)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>~90%</strong></td><td>of <em>new</em> affordable housing, by common estimate (NYT 2012; practitioners concur)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>25%</strong></td><td>of <em>all</em> new U.S. apartment construction, 2000–2019 — not just affordable, all of it</td></tr>
      </table>

      <div class="note">
        <b>Be careful with the 90% figure.</b>
        The New York Times estimated in 2012 that LIHTC had built roughly 90 percent of the nation's affordable housing, and practitioners tell Shelterforce that 85–90% matches their experience. But Shelterforce is candid that no definitive calculation exists — there's no agreement on what counts as an "affordable" project, and the data is scattered across programs and levels of government. The 51% figure, from the National Housing Preservation Database, is the one you can put in front of a hostile reader without a footnote.
      </div>

      <p>The gap between those two numbers <em>is</em> the story. Half of the standing stock, but the overwhelming majority of what's being built now — because there is nothing else left to build with.</p>

      <h2>How it works, in plain terms</h2>
      <p>A developer applies to the state for credits. The state awards them under its <strong>Qualified Allocation Plan</strong> — the rulebook each state writes for itself, which matters enormously and which we'll come back to.</p>
      <p>The developer doesn't usually owe enough federal tax to use the credits. So an investor — typically a bank — buys into the deal and takes the credits instead. That investment is the money that builds the building. The investor claims the credits over <strong>ten years</strong>.</p>
      <p>In exchange, the units must be rented to low-income tenants at restricted rents. The compliance period is <strong>fifteen years</strong>. The extended use period runs another fifteen. Thirty years total, for properties placed in service from 1990 onward.</p>
      <p>Then it's over.</p>

      <h2>Why it expires — and why nobody planned for the ending</h2>
      <p>Here is the thing to hold onto: <strong>every clock in this program is the investor's clock.</strong></p>
      <p>Ten years of credits. Fifteen years of compliance, enforced because the IRS can claw the credits back. Then fifteen more years where the rules technically still apply but the IRS can no longer revoke anything — so enforcement gets much harder, and everyone in the field knows it. Thirty years, and the instrument has finished doing what an instrument does.</p>
      <p>Not one of those numbers is about a person. Nobody asked how long a tenant lives somewhere. Nobody asked what happens to the 62-year-old on the last day of year thirty. The term wasn't cruel — it was simply <em>about something else</em>. It described a financing life, not a human one.</p>

      <blockquote>A housing program would have asked what happens to the tenants. A tax credit asks what happens to the investor's basis. We have spent forty years pretending those are the same question.</blockquote>

      <p>This is also why there is no remedy. Not an inadequate remedy — <strong>none</strong>. The statute has an exit and no landing. When the term ran out on my building, there was no provision to consult, no agency with a duty to act, no process for the seventy families inside. There was just a date, and after it, the market.</p>

      <h2>Who actually lives in LIHTC housing</h2>
      <p>Not the people the program was designed for. This is well known to anyone who manages these buildings and almost never said out loud.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Over half</strong> of LIHTC tenants earn below 30% of area median income — far under the 50–60% the rents are actually set for.</li>
        <li><strong>Fewer than a quarter</strong> fall in the 40–60% band the program nominally targets.</li>
        <li><strong>Two in five</strong> are rent-burdened <em>while living in "affordable" housing</em>. One in eight pays more than half their income in rent.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>They manage because roughly half of them hold a voucher. Which means LIHTC is quietly consuming the rental assistance that would otherwise help people in the private market — while still leaving two-fifths of its own tenants cost-burdened.</p>

      <h2>And this is where "just build more" breaks</h2>
      <p>New York's rental vacancy rate hit <strong>1.41%</strong> in 2023 — the lowest since 1968. That number gets used to argue for building anything, anywhere, as fast as possible. But the crisis isn't evenly distributed. It isn't close.</p>

      <table>
        <tr><th>Monthly rent</th><th>Vacancy rate</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Under $1,100</td><td><strong style="color:var(--red)">0.39%</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>$1,100 – $1,649</td><td><strong style="color:var(--red)">0.91%</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>$2,400 and above</td><td><strong>3.39%</strong></td></tr>
      </table>

      <p>The apartments are not missing. <strong>The cheap apartments are missing.</strong> There is something close to a functioning market at the top and no market at all at the bottom, and a citywide average smears those two facts into one misleading number.</p>

      <div class="note">
        <b>What the shortage actually looks like</b>
        <strong>703,628</strong> households need rents below $1,100. <strong>2,297</strong> such apartments were vacant and available. (ANHD)<br><br>
        Fewer than <strong>5,000</strong> apartments were available to the 1.17 million households earning under $50,000 — 36% of the city. Meanwhile <strong>33,000+</strong> were available to the 16% earning over $200,000. (Community Service Society)<br><br>
        Between 1993 and 2023, New York City lost over <strong>600,000</strong> apartments renting at or below $1,500 (inflation-adjusted) — and gained <strong>75,000</strong> renting over $5,000. (CSS)<br><br>
        <strong>86%</strong> of households earning under $25,000 without rental assistance spend more than half their income on rent. (NYCHVS 2023)
      </div>

      <p>New market-rate construction does not fill that hole. Apartments listed in 2023 had a median asking rent of $3,500 or more. Building more of those is not a response to a 0.39% vacancy rate at $1,100.</p>

      <blockquote>We do not have a housing crisis. We have an <em>affordability</em> crisis — and we keep answering it with supply at a price nobody in the crisis can pay.</blockquote>

      <p>None of which is an argument against building. Build. But building is not a substitute for <strong>tools</strong>, and right now we are short of tools, not enthusiasm. Deeply affordable housing has to be subsidized — there is no market mechanism that produces a $900 apartment on the Columbia Street waterfront. So the question is never <em>whether</em> to subsidize. It's what we get for the subsidy, and for how long.</p>
      <p>Under LIHTC, we pay for thirty years and then hand the asset to the market. That is the worst possible answer, and it's the one we've chosen by default — not because we decided it was right, but because we let the last tool in the box become the plan.</p>

      <h2>The good news, which is real</h2>
      <p>None of this is inevitable, and the proof is already running. The federal minimum is 30 years — but states write their own Qualified Allocation Plans, and they can demand more. <strong>Vermont requires affordability in perpetuity.</strong> It has since the early 2000s. And the thing the industry always warns will happen, didn't: Vermont gets <strong>two to three times more developer demand than it has credits to award</strong>, with a waiting list.</p>

      <table>
        <tr><th>State</th><th>Affordability term</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Vermont</td><td><strong>Permanent</strong></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Oregon</td><td>60 years</td></tr>
        <tr><td>California</td><td>55 years</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Massachusetts, Montana, Utah</td><td>50 years</td></tr>
        <tr><td>National average</td><td>~42 years</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>New York</strong></td><td><strong style="color:var(--red)">30 years</strong></td></tr>
      </table>

      <blockquote>New York requires the federal minimum — below the national average — in the most expensive housing market in the country.</blockquote>

      <p>That is a choice. It was made by us, it can be unmade by us, and it does not require a single dollar from Washington.</p>

      <h2>What we're asking for</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Permanent affordability.</strong> Vermont has run the experiment for twenty years. The objection has been tested and it failed.</li>
        <li><strong>At absolute minimum, extend New York's term.</strong> Sixty years means most tenants outlive the clock. Thirty means they don't.</li>
        <li><strong>A right to know your expiration date.</strong> Tenants are not told. Landlords sometimes don't know. In my building, the attorneys on both sides disagreed and the date was settled by negotiation.</li>
        <li><strong>Preservation funding at scale</strong>, and the power for tenants and nonprofits to buy — <strong>TOPA</strong> and <strong>COPA</strong>. These are triage. They catch a building on its way out the door. They do not remove the door.</li>
      </ul>

      <blockquote>Affordability shouldn't come with an expiration date.</blockquote>

